  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions developed gradually over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged primarily in response to organized crime activities\n- Initial focus on concealing proceeds from illegal enterprises\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act of 1970 - First comprehensive anti-money laundering legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report significant cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Progression:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention addressed drug trafficking proceeds\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established international standards\n- Recommended comprehensive regulatory frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n4. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- 1986 Money Laundering Control Act (US)\n- 1990 European Community Directive on money laundering\n- 2001 USA PATRIOT Act significantly expanded enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Modern Characteristics:\n- Increasingly complex regulatory requirements\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Expanded scope beyond traditional criminal enterprises\n- Incorporating technological developments like cryptocurrency regulations\n\n6. Current Trends:\n- Increasingly sophisticated detection technologies\n- Greater emphasis on global coordination\n- Stricter penalties and enforcement mechanisms\n\nThis represents a broad overview of money laundering prohibition's legal evolution.",
